Here's a simple example of a web app called "MattF" that includes HTML, CSS, and JavaScript all in a single file. This example creates a basic web page with a title, a button, and a message that changes when the button is clicked.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>MattF Web App</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            background-color: #f4f4f4;
            margin: 0;
            padding: 20px;
        }
        h1 {
            color: #333;
        }
        button {
            padding: 10px 20px;
            font-size: 16px;
            background-color: #007BFF;
            color: white;
            border: none;
            border-radius: 5px;
            cursor: pointer;
        }
        button:hover {
            background-color: #0056b3;
        }
        #message {
            margin-top: 20px;
            font-size: 18px;
            color: #555;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Welcome to MattF Web App</h1>
    <button id="changeMessageButton">Click Me!</button>
    <div id="message"></div>

    <script>
        document.getElementById('changeMessageButton').addEventListener('click', function() {
            document.getElementById('message').innerText = 'Hello, you clicked the button!';
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:
- **HTML Structure**: The document includes a header, a button, and a div for displaying messages.
- **CSS Styles**: Basic styles are applied to the body, heading, button, and message for better presentation.
- **JavaScript Functionality**: An event listener is added to the button, which changes the text of the message div when clicked.

You can copy and paste this code into a `.html` file and open it in a web browser to see the web app in action.
